title.narrative: She Leads Kenya: Increased Influence of GYWs in decision making in formal and informal institutions in Kenya

description.narrative: The project aims to promote the institutionalization of meaningful participation and influence of GYW in both formal and informal institutions in a just and inclusive environment which is important for promoting gender equity and equality.

comment.narrative: Activities under this outcome are planned for Q3 going forward;

Progress under this outcome is attributed to sensitization on SASA together phase one conducted to Community Activities from 3-sub-Counties of implementation in Kwale (Matuga, Lunga Lunga and Msambweni). SASA together is an approach that supports actions for social change targeting: leaders of organized community groups and associations (youth, men and women) that have an influence on social norms. Second phase of SASA together will be conducted in 2022 as a buildup on the training conducted these years (2021) to equip Cas with knowledge to sensitize community on power dynamics and social norms change in their communities;

comment.narrative: The under expenditure is due to conference package which was slightly cheaper than budgeted. The activity is complete. Under achievement is attributed to 2 CAs dropping out at mobilization level, only 28 CAs were trained . Output was informed by media training of 11-journalists (14 to 24 yrs. - 1-F; 25 to 30 yrs. - 2-F & 1-M & above 30 yrs. - 5-F & 2-M) on gender reporting and sensitization of 28 CAs (20-F; 8-M) on SASA together to equip the CAs with skills and knowledge to lead their communities in retrospective reflection to enhance social norms change; and spark community-wide change and transforming imbalances of power. Over achievement realized under journalists training was as a result of one of the media stations requesting an extra slot to undertake the sensitization.;

comment.narrative: Achievements under this output are informed by preparatory meeting with 7-civil society reps with a participation of 7-Females all above 30 yrs. Also, sensitization on advocacy to 7-civil society entities at National level to determine GYW priority issues & identify advocacy spaces for GYW engagement. A total of 19-GYW participated with 14 to 24 yrs. - 3F, 25 to 30 yrs. - 8F & 2M and above 30 yrs. - 6F. Emerging issues: Retrogressive policies, Harmful traditional practices i.e., Child marriage, inadequate disability inclusive SRH services etc. - formed part of agenda for Sub Activity 2.1.2.1. L&A Sensitization to GYW/ Feminist-led orgs. The budget in PRIMUS is Eur 74 but what we have is Eur 368 for this activity. We spent Eur 309.92;

This activity is being informed by the mapping exercise which will provide information CSOs, GYW engagement, interventions capacity needs/ gaps. This information will inform the nature of capacity building to be undertaken. GEM has planned to conduct this activity in Q 3 since after the mapping exercise report has been developed. The target will be achieved after this activity is conducted.;

comment.narrative: Activity implemented here is 2.3.2 which is ongoing with an expenditure as of 30th Sept of Eur 1,499 spent out of Eur 1,624 budget. Activity was conducted jointly at National level in Homabay, Kisumu, Kwale and Nairobi Counties. Conducted to establish baseline information & data on key components including: data on discriminatory gender norms, identify key stakeholders who inform the programme’s objective, identify gaps in implementation coverage, identify areas of linkage & synergies. Respective partners undertook their own mapping in Counties of implementation & consolidated report that were shared with GEM for compilation into one report at the national level. Consolidated draft report is ready.;

Mapping exercise was not completed as planned being that it's a joint activity that needed contribution from all consortium partners. No budget was utilized. Only preparatory activities were conducted in Q2 i.e., development of TOR;

comment.narrative: Achievement was attributed to inception meeting conducted with 8 govt. officials; & follow-up meetings conducted with the various Ministries (13 officials) met during inception meeting to further consolidate the areas of synergy earlier discussed the modalities as well for partnership. With this, GEM in partnership with Ministry of youth and ICT enrolled 6 GYWs to be trained as mental health champions. What is in PRIMAS is the budget of Eur 205 for 3.1.2. What we implemented is 3.1.1 which has a budget of Eur 590. We spent Eur 588;

Joint National Inception meeting was conducted jointly with consortium partners. Each partner contributed to the planning process however GEM did not utilize any budget during the joint inception meeting. GEM had two slots of government official representatives to invite; only 1-female attended the meeting (representative from State Department of Gender & Youth affairs);

comment.narrative: No budget was utilized; the budget will be used in Q4. The use of this budget is dependent on the approval of messages by the TdH team. We hope to get approval in time for Dec messaging and the budget will be fully utilized (Ksh.13,000). This was a joint activity where partners were to jointly develop messages & share for approval; and design & print IEC materials for use in social media campaign. This did not work thus GEM's decision to partner with Plan International to commemorate International Youth Day by (1) taking GYW through Inclusion, safeguarding, power dynamics and sustainability concept under She Leads project (2) Utilizing social media platform - GEM Trust Twitter (@GEM_Africa) to push for the theme of the day by retweeting messages.;

Under achievement is due to need to conduct a kickoff meeting which was a prerequisite for implementation of all other activities in the approved work plan, the Menstrual Hygiene Day on 28th May also falls on the day the kick off was ending hence could not be conducted. The International day for the elimination of the sexual violence on 19th June was overtaken by events as all efforts were concentrated on ensuring that the two set up activities were conducted. To ensure that relevant days are commemorated and both financial and programme targets achieved, GEM will commemorate the international youth day and the international day of the girl child.;

comment.narrative: The overachievement in target is attributed to 3-GYW supported to participate in youth forum-EAC SRH bill. under expenditure is due to Activity 3.3.1 not being implemented-pegged on convener’s schedule which is yet TBC; though a preparatory meeting with 3-GYW for UPR meeting was conducted-expenditure of Eur 297 out of budget Eur 1573. Bal. will be used to support GYW to the actual UPR meeting. Activity 3.3.2. rescheduled to Q4, the budget will be utilized during the actual activity on 6th Dec. Activity 3.3.3 GEM supported 3-GYW from Kwale to participate in EAC SRH bill review forum-expenditure of Eur 1491 out of a budget of 2393. The bal. is for the meeting with duty bearers to be conducted in Q4, as the activity was in 2- folds, for CSOs and Govt. officials. which will be done in Q4.;

Under this activity, the processes that GEM has identified will be having national level engagements in August i.e. The Universal peer review (UPR) and East African Community SRH bill. GEM will support GYWs to engage in these processes. The scheduling of these the regional and international processes is determined by the conveners hence GEM had to reschedule this engagement to fit within the timelines set by conveners;
